                <p>@Html.Raw(@Model.NewsSummary.Replace("\n", "<br>"))</p>
                <p>In a bold move to address the rising number of road accidents involving two-wheelers, the Indian government has announced new safety regulations focused on mandatory helmet standards and the promotion of essential riding gear. Starting in 2024, all helmets sold in India must carry the ISI certification to ensure proper protection. This regulation aligns with the goal to reduce the alarming number of fatalities linked to improper head protection in motorcycle crashes.</p>
                <p>Furthermore, the government is rolling out incentives, including tax benefits and subsidies, to encourage bikers to invest in protective riding gear such as jackets, gloves, boots, and guards. These new policies follow the latest data showing that motorcyclists represent nearly 37% of road fatalities in the country. The government hopes that by ensuring the use of certified safety gear, it can decrease the severity of injuries and improve survival rates in accidents.</p>
                <p>Experts and road safety activists have welcomed this development, highlighting how affordable and readily available safety gear can bridge the gap in accident prevention. Manufacturers of safety equipment are also preparing to ramp up production to meet the anticipated surge in demand, with many planning to offer new lines of certified products.</p>
                <p>This proactive approach could change the landscape of biker safety in India, saving countless lives and creating a culture where safety comes first.</p>
